DESIGN METHODOLOGY
   * we will use postgresql architecture over (mysql like) mini transactions
   * we will have heap_table for storing tables, insert to which gives us a page_id (physical page_id) and a tuple_index (slot no) in that page
   * indexes will always include the page_id, tuple_index in the index key right after the actual key columns, and the index entry will be index key followed by the covering columns
   * inserts to table
     * insert row in heap_table
     * insert all index entries in all indexes, only after heap table row is inserted
   * true deletion only happens in trash_cleaner job (aka postgresql's vaccum)
     * scan heap_table and find the rows on a page that need to be discarded
     * discard all the index entries for these row
     * only then discard the heap_table row
   * This above ordering ensures that we will never find an index entry that has a dangling heap tuple pointer
     * i.e. on following an index entry, we will always find something
   * inserts/deletes will always be done to heap in a single mini transaction one at a time
   * inserts/deletes to indexes will be done in mini transactions not owned by anyone
   * updates are just logical delete (xmax = self) followed by an actual insert into the heap
   * reads will be be done without mini transactions, but in a fixed number of them, controlled by the resource usage limiter of the bufferpool
   * there will be trash_cleaner, like postgresql's vaccum
   * header will include xmin, xmax, is_xmin_committed?, is_xmax_committed?, is_xmin_aborted?, is_xmax_aborted? and both of which can be NULL
     * xmin, xmax will be as wide as transaction_table suggests
     * the *? are advisory bitmaps and should be kept updated when ever a heap page is being read (if only a read lock on page is held then let another writer do it asynchronously) or written

